data.content:
In xUnit, there are no setup/teardown attributes. Instead, it uses constructor/`IDisposable` for per-test lifecycle and `IClassFixture<T>` for shared class-level lifecycle:

```csharp
// Shared class-level setup/teardown → fixture class
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // [OneTimeSetUp]
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // [OneTimeTearDown]
    }
}

// [TestFixture] → no attribute needed
public class CustomerRepositoryTests
    : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor = [SetUp] (runs before each test)
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable.Dispose = [TearDown] (runs after each test)
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]  // [Test] → [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` | `IClassFixture<T>` constructor |
| `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>.Dispose()` |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |

The `DatabaseFixture` is instantiated once and shared across all tests in the class. If you need to share it across multiple test classes, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` with a `[Collection]` attribute instead.
